aks (ic akr)
akt (akb aks)
aku "why drawing instructions and not pixels?"
akv (ic aku)
akw "Initially, I tried to communicate with the outside world using pixel graphics. However, I believe that's not the right move as pixels are more difficult to handle in code. Having pixels (or some concept ofa texture) within this notebook requires either:\n- mutable values (which don't exist in here), or\n- lots of copying on every texture modification, or\n- a super-smart optimizing compiler (which is useful but it has the sort of slow-by-default-and-you-have-to-trust-the-black-box-to-work feeling I don't like), or\n- inefficient storage of individual pixels in trees."
akx (ic akw)
aky (akb akx)
akz "By communicating the intent on a quite high-level, we can instead make use of GPUs when turning the high-level drawing instructions into pixels. This is also similar to how Flutter works: The Dart VM is decently fast, but not super fast, so it just emits drawing instructions that the lower-level C++ engine takes and turns into pixels."
ala (ic akz)
alb (akb ala)
alc (ajz aky alb)
ald (ajv akv alc)
ale (ajr ald)
alf "Within this notebook, code usually returns structs of the form (& draw DrawingInstruction width Float height Float) rather than just a raw instruction."
